The slope \(m_{\text{sec}}\) of the secant line through the points \(\bigl(x_{1},f(x_{1})\bigr)\) and \(\bigl(x_{2},f(x_{2})\bigr)\) is given by  

\[
m_{\text{sec}} \;=\; \frac{f(x_{2}) - f(x_{1})}{\,x_{2}-x_{1}} \quad\text{(Equation 3.1)}
\]

1. Evaluate the function at each \(x\)-value.

   • \(f(1)=\dfrac{4}{3(1)-1}=\dfrac{4}{2}=2\)

   • \(f(3)=\dfrac{4}{3(3)-1}=\dfrac{4}{8}=\dfrac12\)

2. Compute the slope.

\[
m_{\text{sec}}
= \frac{f(3)-f(1)}{3-1}
= \frac{\;\dfrac12 - 2\;}{2}
= \frac{\;\dfrac{1}{2}-\dfrac{4}{2}\;}{2}
= \frac{-\dfrac{3}{2}}{2}
= -\frac34
\]

Therefore, the slope of the secant line between \(x_1 = 1\) and \(x_2 = 3\) is \(-\dfrac34\) (or \(-0.75\)).

